The D peak (∼1350 cm−1) of Raman spectra (Fig. 3
                        ) is observed, which is attributed to the breathing modes of sp2 Carbon atoms in the rings, and G peaks (∼1500 cm−1) are observed due to the bond stretching of sp2 Carbon atoms in rings and chains of the graphitic core of CQDs [22]. The absence of a 2D peak indicates the presence of sp3 carbon atoms that confirms the presence of additional defects. The out of plane vibrations due to structural defects of these systems resulted in a high ID/IG ratio (Table S3, 
                        Supplementary material) [23].

The comparison of IR spectra of CQDs with their modified versions gives evidence for the different functionalities introduced on their surface (
                        Fig. 4

                        ). The broad peak centred at 3300 cm−1 (Fig. 4 (b,d)) comprises OH, NH stretching modes, indicating the amine modification in PP-CQD-NH2 and FP-CQD-NH2. The CH, C-CO, and CO stretching vibrations at 2896 cm−1, 2150 cm−1, and 1650 cm−1, respectively, indicate the presence of carbonyl functionalities in these systems. The CC stretching around 1500 cm−1 corresponds to the sp2 vibrations arising from the graphitic layers of CQDs. CQDs' aggregation results from the hydrophilic behaviour rendered by the functionalities at the edges, while the graphitic core remains hydrophobic [24]. The combined effects of intermolecular hydrogen bonding and π-π stacking between the graphitic cores result in the aggregation and formation of relatively large amorphous particles (∼12 nm) as observed in the TEM images of FP-CQD.

The XPS survey spectra confirm the presence of heteroatoms in these systems (
                        Fig. 5

                        ). The CQDs have an abundance of carboxylic acid functionalities, carbonyl groups and graphitic layers within them (Fig. 6
                        ). The peak at 399 eV of the deconvoluted Nitrogen (N 1s) spectra confirms the presence of only one type of Nitrogen atom (0.4% and 1.8% Nitrogen content in PP-CQD-NH2 and FP-CQD-NH2, respectively) (Fig. 7

                        ). The deconvoluted O 1s peak positioned at 535.48 eV corresponds to the moisture absorbed by the sample from the surroundings (Fig. 6b) [25].

The PL mechanism of CQDs is typically explained based on the synergistic effects of their relative sizes, defects, pH, degree of graphitization, etc. [33,34]. The size of the CQD systems under investigation has little impact on their PL [35]. The combined effects of intrinsic and extrinsic emissions originating from the isolated sp2 carbon hexagons and functionalities are attributed to the fluorescence behaviour [36]. The Tauc plot furnishes the trend where CQDs are bestowed with the characteristics of indirect bandgap materials, and the surface states induced by amine modification are responsible for PL (Fig. 10). The estimated fluorescence lifetimes (Fig. 11

                        ) of CQDs that improved after the amine functionalization are explained in this context (Table S7, 
                        Supplementary material
                        ). Thus, amine functionalization helped tune the bandgap, thereby improving fluorescence lifetimes.

The emission intensity was measured by exciting both PP-CQD-NH2 and FP-CQD-NH2 at 250 nm, and the corresponding emission peaks were obtained at 433 and 426 nm, respectively. Upon the incremental addition of CQDs, the emission intensity increased with a blue shift (Δλ = 3 nm) for PP-CQD-NH2 and with a redshift (Δλ = 4 nm) for FP-CQD-NH2 (Fig. 14
                           ). By analysing the fluorescence behaviour, a mechanism for the interaction of CQDs with DNA can be formulated. The emission enhancement of PP-CQD-NH2 with a blue shift can be attributed to the effective insertion of the amino groups of the probe into the hydrophobic environment of DNA, thereby suppressing its ability to form hydrogen bonds with the solvent molecules. However, the FP-CQD-NH2 showed less efficiency in this regard, presumably due to the difference in surface functionality arising from the difference in precursors. The binding constants (Kb) corresponding to PP-CQD-NH2 and FP-CQD-NH2 were determined using the Benesi-Hilderbrand equation [39] and is summarised in Table 1
                           . Lower value of Kb for FP-CQD-NH2 indicates lesser efficiency of binding to DNA.
